Doctor’s Helper¶

The following report contains comprehensive analysis of the medical data gathered in the local hospital, which concern the health and environmental factors of its patients. Additionally, it introduces the machine learning model which aims to identify patients' attributes which make them more likely to have a disease. The model can be important tool in helping doctors to detect patients at higher risk of getting ill faster and, thanks to that, start the treatment in the early stage of a disease.

1. Data Exploration¶

The following section shows the contents of the records in analysed dataset and summarizes the main characteristics of the patients. The dataframe consists of 13 attributes and contains information about 768 female patients - their blood chemistry, blood pressure, number of pregnancies, skin thickness, BMI, genetic predispositions to disease, their age, state where they live and its air condidtion. It is also known which patient is ill.

The descriptive statistics below indicates that the average patient was pregnant about 4 times. The mean results of blood chemistry I and II are 121.9 and 79.8 respectively. The second variable characterizes much higher standard deviation what means that the values often differ significantly from the average. The reason is that more than 25% of the blood chemistry II data are equal to 0.0. The avarage blood pressure among the patients equal 69.1, while average skin thickness is 20.5. It can be noticed that some attributes, eg. BMI or skin thickness equal 0 while is not valid value for them. Additionally, some columns take improbable big values, eg. maximum age in the dataset is equal to 230. Such observations will be handled further in this report. The descriptive statistics for the remaining columns can be seen in the table below.

In [15]:
# Label pregnancies greater than given threshold
# To make the countplot looking more clear
def label_greater_than(v, threshold):
    if v > threshold:
        return f"> {threshold}"
    else: return str(int(v))
pregnancy_thr = 8
df['pregnancies_ctg'] = df['pregnancies'].apply(lambda x: str(label_greater_than(x, pregnancy_thr)))
ctgs = [str(x) for x in list(range(0, pregnancy_thr+1))]
ctgs.append(f'> {pregnancy_thr}')
df['pregnancies_ctg'] = pd.Categorical(df['pregnancies_ctg'], categories=ctgs, ordered=True)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 5))
sns.countplot(x ='pregnancies_ctg', hue = "outcome", data = df)
ax.set(xlabel='Pregnancies', ylabel='Count')
plt.legend(title='Is patient ill?', loc='upper right', labels=['No', 'Yes'])
df.drop(columns=['pregnancies_ctg'], inplace=True)
plt.show()

For better understanding of blood chemistry III variable, for every 5 measurements of each patient we calculted the mean, standard deviation, median and variance coefficient. Next, all computed metrics were plotted on the histograms to check if probability of being ill depend on the mean, median or degree of volatility of the blood III measurements. Because histograms for both sick and healthy patients look similar, one can infer that neither mean nor volatility of blood III samples affect the probability of positive diagnosis.

In [18]:
blood_3_df = df[['id', 'outcome', *measure_no]].copy()
blood_3_df['median'] = blood_3_df[measure_no].median(axis=1)
blood_3_df['mean'] = blood_3_df[measure_no].mean(axis=1)
blood_3_df['sd'] = blood_3_df[measure_no].std(axis=1)
blood_3_df['cv'] = blood_3_df['sd'] / blood_3_df['mean']

On the histograms below, one can notice that distribution of blood chemistry I and II for ill differs between ill and healthy patients. Individuals diagnosed as ill tend to have higher values of both blood components. Apart from that, almost 50% observations take 0 value for blood chemistry II. Because it is not possible to say with certainty whether 0 is a valid value in this column, it was decided to not treat those values as missing and keep them as they are. On the other hand, blood chemistry I also contains some 0-values which significantly differ from the remaining values. In this case, zero values are more likely to be considered as missing values.

The diagonal of the plot below consists of density plots of variables analysed in this section. The plots being outside the diagonal shows the relationship between each pair of values: blood preassure, skin thickness, age and BMI. Apparently, there is a positive, linear relationship between skin thickness and BMI of the patient. What is more, the plots provide some evidence that patients who have higher blood pressure, thicker skin or are overweight, are at higher risk of becoming ill. It is also noticable that the likelihood of getting the disease increases with age.

Genetic predisposition factor¶

The following plot shows how the values of patients' genetic predisposition factor are distributed. There are some patients with abnormally higher value of this attribute who were diagnosed as ill. Looking at those pattients one can see that they also have high value of blood I component and high BMI. At the same time, patients with high genetic predisposition factor but low BMI and blood chemistry I are healty. It gives some evidences that patients with very high genetic predisposition factor are not necessarily sick. Because high values of the analysed feature do not bring any insight into the anaysis but are far from other data points, they were removed.

State and air quality¶

The dataset contains ifnormation about the state where each individual lives. The table below shows which state characterizes proportion of positively diagnosed patients higher than the proportion in the whole population. These states includes Arkansas, Florida, California and Alabama.

To not include to many categorical variables in the model, every state was assigned to its corresponding region: South, West, Midwest or Northeast. One state named KU, which doesn't match any state in the mapping, was replaced by the most frequent value. Apparently, patients who live in the southern part of the USA are more likely to get ill. At the same time, the bad air quality of the patient's hometown doesn't increase the risk of getting ill.

Correlation¶

The plot included below describes the degree of linear relationship between each two features in the dataset. The highest correlation occures between BMI and skin thickness (0.68) and between blood pressure and age (0.35) of the patients. The reason of higher correlation between age and number of pregnancies is obvious. The correlation between level of component I and II in the blood is also relatively high and equals 0.32. It means that patients who have high blood chemistry I tend to have high blood chemistry II as well.

k-NN Imputation for missing values¶

Because missing data may reduce the predictive ability of the ML model and decrease the representativeness of the observations, in the following report they were imputed with use of k-NN Imputation technique. k-NN Imputer is looking for k nearest observations lying in the neighborhood of point with missing attribute and replace it with the mean value of its nearest neighbors. The choose of k parameter was made with taking into consideration the fact that k should be an odd number, not too big to not overfit the model and not to big to not get too much generalized predictions. Because algorithm uses distance metric, it is sensitive to features' scale. For that reason, before applying k-NN imputation, the data were scaled. Additionally, categorical variable region was replaced by numeric value indicating fraction of ill patients living in such location. Each method was conducted separately on the train and test set to prevent information leakage.

Feature selection with Mutual Information Classifier¶

Before training the model, the least relevant features were removed from the X set based on Mutual Information metric. It measures the dependence between two variables, so, in other words, the extent to which the values of one variable explain the values of another variable. It can be seen at the plot of features importance below, that variables with the highest predictive power of the patient's illness are blood component I and BMI. Some information gain about patient health is also obtained with the results about their blood chemistry II and skin thickness. Almost no information gain is given by data about patient living region and its air quality. Finally, to build the model, it was decided to use all variables except region and air quality.

Random Forest classifier¶

The model built to help doctors in diagnosing patients is random forest classifier. The model uses multiple decision trees and make a decision on the basis of majority vote. When constructing each node of decision tree, only a small part of all features is considered. It prevents model from using the same, strongest predictors when building the trees. As a result many uncorrelated decision trees are created which predictions are avaraged to obtain a final classification decision.

Before training the model, hyperparameter tuning was conducted to select the combination of model parameters giving the lowest cross-validation test error rate. It was done with use of randomized search, which search through random values selected from the parameter space we define. The method indicated a set of following optimal hyperparameters:

  • number of trees in the forest: 200
  • method of calculating maximum number of features to consider at each split: square root of total number of features
  • maximum depth of tree: 4 levels
  • minimum samples present in the leaf node: 11
  • minimum number of observations to split the node: 30

Hyperparameter tuning¶

Fitting the model¶

The random forest classifier was fit on the parameters found from the random search. The train accuracy of the model is 0.799 what means that 79.9% patient from the trainset were correctly classified. The test accuracy is higher and equals 0.87 which can be interpreted the same way - 87% patients from the test set were correctly diagnosed by the model. The AUC score which provides an aggregate measure of model performance across all possible thresholds of classification equals 81.9%.

Confusion matrix¶

A confusion matrix gives a picture of classification model performance and the types of errors it produced. The trained random forest classifier having a threshold of classification set to 0.5 gives precision equal to 100%, recall equal to 63.9% and specificity equal to 100%. It means that 100% of patients thought by the classifier to have the disease, actually have the disease. Value of recall (and sensitivity) says that out off all people that have the disease, only 63.9% got positive diagnose. Specificity indicates that 100% of healthy patients were classified to the correct class. The F1 score which measures both the precision and recall equals 78%.

Adjusting classification threshold¶

In the medical industry, it is common to look for specificity and recall (sensitivity) to evaluate the model performance. Sensitivity is a measure of how well the classifier detects cases of people that have a disease. If recall=1, that means that all patients with the disease are classified correctly. Another important metric is specificity which says how many negative model predictions are actually negative.

In the following case, the classifier gives the right diagnose for 100% healthy persons, but at the same time miss more than 26% of the disease cases. Because classifying a sick patient as healthy can have much worse consequences than classifying a healthy person as sick, the model should be improved to have possibly high recall at the lowest loss on accuracy and specificity. Healthy patients can undergo further testing to confirm the presence of the disease, while no treatment may have a significant impact on health of ill patients. It is possible to increase the recall of the model by changing the classification threshold. The new threshold for the discussed classificar was set to 0.35, what means that patients having probabilty of disease higher than 35% are classified as ill. On the other hand, patients with probability lower than 35% get negative diagnose. Changing the threshold led to an increase in recall from 63.9% to 86.1%. Now, 86.1% of all patients with disease are classified correctly. The F1 score is also higher now and equals 78.5%. The increase of recall was done at the cost of decrease of precision which now takes a value of 72.1%.

To better illustrate how the model works, the chart below shows 1 of the 300 decision trees that the forest consists of. The decision tree shown below makes a decision about patient diagnose based on the rules present in the nodes. The first decision is made based on the patient age. Next the patient blood chemistry I or II is checked, depend on the decision made in the first node. The decisions are made in the similar way as long as the patient become classified into particular class. Then the process is repeated for the remaining 299 tree estimators and person is diagnosed according to the majority vote of all the trees.

To show how the value of model prediction behaves as a function of a selected explanatory variable, the partial dependence profiles were shown below. The plots explaines how the predicted probability of patient's illness would behave as the result of change of one feature. It can be noted that on average an increase of blood chemistry I from 80 to 180 increases the probability of patient's illness by 30%. Blood chemistry II is not such strong predictor, nevertheless, change of its value from 100 to 300 makes the patient 4% more likely to get ill. Interestingly, the probability of getting ill increase significantly (by almost 10%) when a woman reaches the age of 30. Another strong predictor is BMI. The 6th plot indicates that the patient with BMI eual to 45 is at much higher risk of getting sick (13% higher probability) than the same patient with BMI equal to 25. The predictors significantly influencing the model decisions also includes the skin thickness, genetic predisposition factor and number of pregnancies. For example, patient with skin thickness equal to 20 is on average about 12% less likely to get ill than the same patient with skin thickness equal to 35. The predictor which change does not affect the model prediction significantly is patient's blood pressure.

Conclusion¶

The aim of the following report was to introduce the machine learning model which is meant to help doctors from the local hospital make better and faster decisions diagnosing their patients. The random forest model was built and it achieved the accuracy score equal to 83% which means that classifier gives correct diagnose in 85% cases. The classification threshold of the model was adjusted to increase the model ability to give positive diagnosis for people who actually have a disease. The recall of final model takes value of 86.1% indicating percentage of patients with disease who are classified correctly. At the same time, 81.2% healthy people got negative results from the model. The following report also helped to identify the most important factors that influence the risk of getting ill. The strongest predictors of the investigated disease are patient's results of blood chemistry I and BMI. Other important fetures that increase the risk of getting ill are patient's age, skin thickness and genetic predisposition factor.

The accuracy, recall and specificity of the model are to low to trust the classifier decisions without any doubt. On the other hand, the model can still be an important tool, helping doctors faster detect patients at higher risk of having disease, if used under the supervision of an expert in the specific medical field. What is more, it helped to identify the most important biological charasterictics of patients that affect their probability of illness. Finally, the model can be improved in the future by training on a larger dataset and performing more comprehensive hyperparameter tunning with use of wider parameter space.
